{"title_page": "Lawrence Realization Stakes", "text_new": "{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Discontinued stakes\n| horse race    = Lawrence Realization Stakes \n| website       = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Belmont Park]]<br>[[Elmont, New York]], [[United States]]\n| inaugurated   = 1889 \n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| distance      = {{frac|1|1|8}} miles (9 furlongs)\n| surface       = Dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Three-year-olds\n| weight        =\n| purse         = \n| bonuses       = \n}}\n\nThe '''Lawrence Realization Stakes''' was an [[United States|American]] [[horse racing|horse race]] first run on the turf in 1889. The race, for three-year-old [[Thoroughbred]] colts, geldings and fillies, was last run in 2005.\n\n==History==\nInaugurated at the [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]] at [[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend, New York]], it was held there until 1913. At that time, the race was the richest stakes for three-year-olds in the United States.\n\nIt was run as the Realization Stakes until 1899, when it was renamed to honor James G. K. Lawrence, president of the [[Coney Island Jockey Club]] (which owned the racetrack). Lawrence was also responsible for creating of the [[Belmont Futurity Stakes|Futurity Stakes]] in 1888.\n\nThe stakes were later run at [[Belmont Park]] on [[Long Island]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVUwAAAAIAAJ&q=lawrence+realization+stakes+1899&dq=lawrence+realization+stakes+1899&hl=en&ei=GrWATIu-JZGSswbR2e2nBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAQ]''Chicago Daily News Almanac and Yearbook'' vol. 47, p. 507. ''Chicago Daily News Co.'', 1931.</ref> as a [[Graded stakes race|Grade II]] race on the dirt. The race continued to be run there (except for the Belmont Park redevelopment period from 1962 to 1968) until it was removed from the calendar in 2005 by the [[New York Racing Association]] (NYRA) as a cost-cutting measure. For 70 years, the Lawrence Realization was one of the most prestigious annual events in the American [[horse racing]] calendar.\n\nOnly two horses contested the race in 1918, 1920, 1944, and 1946; however, due to the large number of entries in 1976 and 1985 it was run in two divisions.\n\nThe race was contested over several distances: \n* 1\u215d miles : 1889-1913, 1918-1969\n* 1\u00bd miles : 1916-1917, 1970-2004\n* 1\u215b miles : 2005\n\n==Records==\nOn September 4, 1920, [[Man o' War]] won the 1\u215d-mile Lawrence Realization by 100 lengths over the only other runner, Hoodwink. His time for the race was 2:40 4/5, which broke the world record for the distance by 1 3/5 seconds and was his fifth record-setting performance that year. The great [[Kelso (horse)|Kelso]] tied the record in 1960.\n\n===Records for distance===\n* At 1\u00bd miles : 2:25.94 - ''Parade Ground'' (1998)\n* At 1\u215d miles : 2:40.80 - ''Man o' War'' (1920)\n* At 1\u215d miles : 2:40.80 - ''Kelso''  (1960)\n\n===Most wins by a [[jockey]]===\n* 5 - [[Braulio Baeza]] (1961, 1966, 1967, 1968, 1972)\n* 5 - [[Eddie Arcaro]] (1935, 1939, 1952, 1959, 1960)\n\n===Most wins by a [[Horse trainer|trainer]]===\n* 8 - [[James E. Fitzsimmons|\"Sunny Jim\" Fitzsimmons]] (1924, 1925, 1930, 1932, 1934, 1936, 1938, 1940)\n\n===Most wins by an owner===\n* 6 - [[Belair Stud]] (1924, 1925, 1930, 1932, 1936, 1940)\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:30px\" | Year<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Winner<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Jockey<br>\n! style=\"width:120px\" | Trainer<br>\n! Owner<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Time<br>\n|-\n\n|align=center|2005\n|Taming The Tiger\n|[[Ramon A. Dominguez|Ramon Dominguez]]\n|Robert P. Klesaris\n|C D and G Stable et al.\n|1:49.72\n|-\n|align=center|2004\n|Gunning For\n|[[Joe Bravo (jockey)|Joe Bravo]]\n|Timothy Walsh\n|Mrs. Thomas J. Walsh\n|2:29.91\n|-\n|align=center|2003\n|Kicken Kris\n|[[Javier Castellano]]\n|[[Michael Matz]